Time of Day: Morning, Afternoon, Night¶

First, we examine how the time of day of the flight impacts 1) delay rate (i.e., frequency of delayed flights out of all flights), delay amount upon departure, and delay amount upon arrival.

In [19]: 
#Split times into morning (1 AM - 12 PM), afternoon (12 PM - 5 PM), and night (5 PM - 12 AM)
test = frm.reset_index(drop=True)
test.head()

col = test[['CRS_DEP_TIME']]
MORNING = (col>=1.0) & (col<=1200)
AFTERNOON = (col>1200) & (col<=1700)
NIGHT  = col>1700
rslt = MORNING.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 2*AFTERNOON.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 3*NIGHT.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0)

#Add time of day column
test['TIME_OF_DAY'] = rslt

#Dataframe for delayed flights only
test_delayed = test[test['DELAYED'] == 1].reset_index(drop=True)
In [51]: 
#Make all delay amounts > 200 = 200 (give better idea of distribution of delay)
test_delayed.loc[:,'ARR_DELAY_NEW'] = test_delayed['ARR_DELAY_NEW'].apply(lambda x: min(x, 200))
test_delayed.loc[:,'DEP_DELAY_NEW'] = test_delayed['DEP_DELAY_NEW'].apply(lambda x: min(x, 200))

#Find top 25 airports
airports = test_delayed.groupby('ORIGIN')
airports_new = airports.aggregate({'YEAR': np.sum}).sort('YEAR',ascending=Falso)
airports25 = airports_new.iloc[range(25)].index

#Top 25 airports (departure airports; delayed flights only)
top_airports = test_delayed.loc[test_delayed['ORIGIN'].apply(lambda x: x in airports25)]

#Top 25 airports(arrival airports; delayed flights only)
top_airports_arrive = test_delayed.loc[test_delayed['DEST'].apply(lambda x: x in airports25)]

#Top 25 airports (departure, and not only delayed data)
top_airports2 = frm.loc[frm['ORIGIN'].apply(lambda x: x in airports25)]

#Top 25 airports (arrival, and not only delayed data)
top_airports3 = frm.loc[frm['DEST'].apply(lambda x: x in airports25)]

Discussion: We see that the time of day seems to account for variability in flight delay -- as we can see in the plots above, flights that happen later in the day are more likely to be delayed. This is consistent with sources that we found previous to beginning this project, and should be an interesting variable to consider in our later analysis.

Month/Day of Week/Airport¶

We look at the month and day of week to see their impact on flight delay. The intuition behind this was that certain months (December, for example, where one might assume there to be more problematic weather) and certain days of the week (Sunday, for example, when airports may be busier) could be more indicative of the likelihood of flight delay. In addition, we look at how different airports may impact flight delay -- some airports may perform worse than others in terms of flight delay.

Discussion: In terms of month, we see that certain months do seem to be related to a higher frequency of delayed flights -- this makes sense intuitively (i.e., holidays during December mean more traffic in airports, as well as an increased likelihood of inclement weather). Flight delays across days of the week seemed to be consistent, and no particular day of the week appeared to give a higher indication of delay than others. Airport seemed to also be a pretty significant player in the variability of flight delay, and is a variable that should be considered in predicting flight delay -- certain airports, ORD for example, have a much higher frequency of delay.

Time of Flight -- Rounded Hour and More Time of Day Analysis¶

Since time of day seemed to yield interesting results, we now look at a more specific factor -- that is, rounded departure time. Times were rounded to the nearest hour. In addition, we compute average delay rate and amount of delay for time of day by grouping the dataframe into Morning (1), Afternoon (2), and Night (3).

In [24]:

Discussion: We see that flight delay follows generally the same trend for the rounded flight departure times as we observed for time of day. That is, later flights generally follow a smooth trend of increased likelihood of flight delay. One outlier in this trend is the flight time of around 3 - 4 AM -- this is not likely because this time actually has a higher rate of delayed flights, but rather may be due to the fact that there are not many flights at this time. As such, the delayed flights at this time may be overemphasized when taking the mean of delay rate and amount of delay. In general, looking at the time of flight seems to give a fairly good indication of how the flight will perform compared to other flights.

Precipitation¶

Next, we move on to looking at weather data. First, we will examine precipitation (in our dataset, this is 'liquidOne', which represents the amount in hundredths of inches of precipitatation one hour prior to the flight time). Initially, we simply use precipitation as it is given in the data, but we find later on that it is more informative to create categories or "buckets" for precipitation data, similarly to how we grouped time of day earlier.

In [31]: 
#Split liquid (precipitation -- origin) into categories (low, moderate, high)
col = test[['liquidOneO']]
REALLY_LOW = (col>=0) & (col<=5)
LOW = (col>5) & (col<=40)
MODERATE  = (col>40) & (col<=80)
MODERATE_HIGH = (col>80) & (col<=200)
HIGH   = (col>200)
rslt2 = REALLY_LOW.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 2*LOW.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 3*MODERATE.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 4*MODERATE_HIGH.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 5*HIGH.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0)
In [32]: 
#Add categorical precipitation (at origin) to dataframe
test['PRECIPITATION_O'] = rslt2
In [33]: 
#Split liquid (precipitation -- destination) into categories (low, moderate, high)
col = test[['liquidOneD']]
REALLY_LOW = (col>=0) & (col<=5)
LOW = (col>5) & (col<=40)
MODERATE  = (col>40) & (col<=80)
MODERATE_HIGH = (col>80) & (col<=200)
HIGH   = (col>200)
rslt3 = REALLY_LOW.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 2*LOW.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 3*MODERATE.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 4*MODERATE_HIGH.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0) + 5*HIGH.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x else 0)

Discussion: As expected, we see that flight delay, when compared to precipitation, does follow a trend -- more severe precipitation seemed to indicate more likely flight delay. In particular, precipitation at the origin airport appeared to greatly impact the rate of delay of flights (i.e., increased precipitation was associated with increased flight delay rate). When looking at the amount of delay, conditional on the flight being delayed, it appears that the amount of delay both ways (at origin and destination) is generally consistent across all levels of precipitation. That is, while precipitation may play a large role in whether the flight is actually is delayed, it isn't highly indicative of the amount of time which the flight will be delayed by. This appears to be especially valid in looking at precipitation at the destination airport (there is a slight increasing trend at the origin airport, though it is not as clear as the trend of increasing rate of delay, as mentioned earlier).

Freezing Precipitation¶

We now look at how precipitation (along with below freezing temperature) affects flight delay. One would expect that freezing precipitation (i.e., snow, sleet, hail) would have a greater impact on the flight delay.

In [40]: 
#When there is precipitation and temp is below freezing (unconditional)
freezing_dep = test[(test['airTempO'] < 0) & (test['PRECIPITATION_O'] > 0)]
freezing_arr = test[(test['airTempD'] < 0) & (test['PRECIPITATION_D'] > 0)]

#When there is precipitation and temp is below freezing (conditional)
freezing_dep_cond = conditional[(conditional['airTempO'] < 0) & (conditional['PRECIPITATION_O'] > 0)]
freezing_arr_cond = conditional[(conditional['airTempD'] < 0) & (conditional['PRECIPITATION_D'] > 0)]

Discussion: We see that having freezing precipitation is a pretty clear indicator of a high rate of flight delay, as one would expect. We also see that there is a downward trend of departure delay amount for increasing freezing precipitation at the destination airport. This may be due to the fact that the flight itself may be cancelled if the weather is too severe at the destination.

Windspeed¶

Another factor to consider is windspeed -- if the windspeed is above a certain bar, a plane may be delayed or cancelled. Thus, we expect that increased wind will be correlated with increased flight delay.

Discussion: Windspeed appears to be a very good predictor of flight delay. Unconditionally, increased windspeed is indicative of increased delay rate. Conditional on the flight actually being delayed, we also see that increased windspeed is associated with increased amount of delay for both origin and destination delay amounts. Of the factors that we have examined, this appears to be one of the most important ones.

Conclusion: Many variables appear to play some role in predicting flight delay, but the ones that appear to be of highest importance based on this data exploration are windspeed, precipitation, flight time, airline carrier, and airport. While preliminary, this exploration allows us to have a reasonable starting point for further analysis and successful predictive ability.¶
